# DFL Framework Architecture

This project uses the Deep Forest Labs (DFL) Unity framework. All runtime code is structured around hierarchical DI containers, field injection, and async lifecycle interfaces.

## Bootstrap Flow

`Main.cs` (framework) runs via `[RuntimeInitializeOnLoadMethod]`. It loads `MainArgs` from `Resources/`, builds the root container, and runs `MainState`:

```csharp
await using (_container = await Container.CreateMain("Main", token)
    .AddSingleton(args)
    .AddFromBuilder(args)
    .AddScoped<MainState>()
    .Build(token))
{
    await _mainState.Run(token);
}
```

Game projects subclass `MainArgs` to register project-specific services and the app `ContainerBuilderFactory`.

## Dependency Injection

Use `[Dependency]` on fields. The container resolves them during `Build()`. NEVER instantiate services or states with `new` -- register them on the builder.

```csharp
// GOOD
public sealed class MyState : IRunnable
{
    [Dependency] private readonly IMyService _service = default!;
    [Dependency] private readonly IContainer _container = default!;
}

// BAD -- bypasses DI, loses lifecycle management
var service = new MyService();
```

### Optional Dependencies

For services that may or may not be registered, use a nullable type with `= default` (not `= default!`):

```csharp
// Required dependency (default -- container throws DiException if not registered)
[Dependency] private readonly IMyService _service = default!;

// Optional dependency (container skips silently if not registered)
[Dependency] private readonly IMyService? _service = default;
```

The container won't throw if nothing registers the type. Always null-check before use. Use sparingly -- most dependencies should be required.

### Registration Methods

| Method | Lifetime | Use for |
|--------|----------|---------|
| `AddScoped<T>()` | One per container build | Services, controllers |
| `AddScoped<IFoo, FooImpl>()` | One per build, interface-keyed | Services with interfaces |
| `AddScoped<T>(Func<IContainer, T>)` | One per build | Services needing constructor args (see Config ScriptableObjects in game patterns) |
| `AddSingleton<T>(instance)` | Shared across container + children | Config, factories |
| `AddTransient<IRunnable, T>()` | Created on demand via `Create<T>` | States (runnables) |
| `AddAlias<IFoo, Foo>()` | Alias an existing registration | Multiple interfaces for one type (also used for `IReadOnlyAsyncReactiveProperty<T>` aliases) |
| `AddFromBuilder(factory)` | Delegates to a `ContainerBuilderFactory` | Composition of scopes |
| `AddChild(factory)` | Delegates to a `Factory` | Register an MVC Factory (Model + View + Controller as a unit) |
| `AddScene<T>()` | One per build | Find MonoBehaviour T in the already-loaded scene |
| `AddScene<T>(sceneRef)` | One per build | Load scene via Addressables, then find T in it |
| `AddScriptableObject<T>()` | One per build | Load a ScriptableObject from Resources at build time |

## Container Hierarchy

Each scope is a child container. Children inherit parent singletons and can add their own registrations. Disposing a child cancels its `CancellationToken` and cleans up its resources.

```csharp
await using (IContainer child = await _container
    .CreateChild("Session")
    .AddFromBuilder(_sessionFactory)
    .Build(token))
{
    await child.Run<IRunnable>(token);
}
// child is disposed here -- scope cancelled, resources freed
```

## ContainerBuilderFactory

Each scope is configured by a `ContainerBuilderFactory` ScriptableObject. Override `AddToBuilder` to register services, child factories, and runnables:

```csharp
public sealed class SessionContainerFactory : ContainerBuilderFactory
{
    [SerializeField] private LevelContainerFactory _levelFactory = default!;

    public override IContainerBuilder AddToBuilder(IContainerBuilder builder)
    {
        return builder
            .AddScoped<ICursorService, CursorService>()
            .AddSingleton(_levelFactory)
            .AddTransient<IRunnable, SessionState>();
    }
}
```

These are ScriptableObject assets assigned in the Unity Inspector, NOT instantiated in code.

## Swarm / Pool Factories (Resolve and Arrange)

When a feature needs a pool of identical MVC entities (enemies, portals, projectiles), use a swarm factory. This is a `ContainerBuilderFactory` that creates N children from the same MVC `Factory`, then collects their controllers into an array for a coordinating manager service.

The build has two phases:

1. **`AddToBuilder`** -- register config, coordinating service, and N children via `AddChild` in a loop.
2. **`ArrangeComponents`** -- after all children are built, collect controller arrays from children and promote the coordinator interface to the parent scope.

```csharp
public sealed class EnemySwarmFactory : ContainerBuilderFactory
{
    [SerializeField] private EnemyFactory _enemyFactory = default!;
    [SerializeField] private int _poolSize = 20;
    [SerializeField] private EnemyManagerConfig _config = default!;

    public override IContainerBuilder AddToBuilder(IContainerBuilder builder)
    {
        builder.AddSingleton(_config);
        builder.AddScoped<IEnemyManager, EnemyManagerService>();
        for (int i = 0; i < _poolSize; i++)
            builder.AddChild(_enemyFactory);
        return builder;
    }

    public override void ArrangeComponents(IArrangeContext context)
    {
        // Collect controllers from the N children into an array for the manager
        // Register the array as a singleton so the manager can inject it
        // Promote the manager interface so the parent scope can inject it
        context.PromoteFrom<IEnemyManager>();
    }
}
```

The parent factory registers the swarm as a child, and the parent state injects the promoted interface:

```csharp
// In GameplayContainerFactory:
builder.AddChild(_enemySwarmFactory);

// In GameplayState:
[Dependency] private readonly IEnemyManager _enemyManager = default!;
```

## Lifecycle Interfaces

| Interface | Purpose | Called by |
|-----------|---------|-----------|
| `IRunnable` | Long-lived async task (`Run(CancellationToken)`) | `container.Run<IRunnable>(token)` |
| `IInitializable` | One-time async setup (`Initialize(CancellationToken)`) | Container during `Build()` |
| `IMainInitializable` | One-time app-level setup before main loop | `MainState` (before app loop) |
| `IDisposable` | Cleanup | Container on scope cancellation |

States implement `IRunnable`. Services that need async setup implement `IInitializable`. The container orchestrates all of these automatically -- do not call `Initialize` or `Dispose` manually.

`IMainInitializable` runs once in `MainState` before the main app loop starts. Use for global bootstrap that must complete before any game scope exists (Addressables initialization, analytics setup, crash reporting). It is an optional dependency -- `MainState` checks for null. Register in `MainArgs`. Different from `IInitializable`, which runs per-scope during `Build()`.

## Error Propagation

The framework handles unhandled exceptions automatically. Game code must NOT catch and swallow exceptions -- let them propagate through the container hierarchy to the framework's error pipeline.

### Exception flow

```
Game code throws (any IRunnable, Controller, Service)
  -> Container scope disposes (CancellationToken cancelled, IDisposable.Dispose called)
    -> Parent container's await completes with the exception
      -> ... bubbles up through container hierarchy ...
        -> MainState catches the exception
          -> IErrorReporter.CaptureException (Sentry reporting)
          -> IMain.ShowingErrorPopup (app lifecycle hook)
          -> IErrorStateController.Run (error UI -- blocks until dismissed)
          -> IMain.DismissingErrorPopup
          -> App loop restarts from the top
```

### What MainState handles

| Exception type | Behavior |
|----------------|----------|
| `OperationCanceledException` | Propagated (scope shutdown) |
| `ResetException` | Logged, app restarts without error UI |
| `RefreshExpiredException` | Runs `IRefreshExpiredState`, then restarts |
| Any other `Exception` | Reported to Sentry, error UI shown, app restarts |

### Game code responsibilities

- Register `IErrorStateController` in `MainArgs` (development: log + return; production: show error popup)
- Register `IErrorReporter` in `MainArgs` (`SentryErrorReporter` for production, `NullErrorReporter` for local dev)
- Implement `IMain` lifecycle hooks (`ShowingErrorPopup`, `DismissingErrorPopup`) if the app needs pre/post error UI behavior
- Do NOT add generic `catch (Exception)` blocks in game states or controllers -- the framework already handles this
